'''Buchanan Township''' is a [[civil township]] of [[Berrien County, Michigan|Berrien County]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Michigan]].  As of the [[United States 2000 Census|2000 census]], the township population was 3,510. The city of [[Buchanan, Michigan|Buchanan]] is located in the southeast portion of the township.

Buchanan Township is bounded by [[Oronoko Charter Township, Michigan|Oronoko Township]] to the north, [[Berrien Charter Township, Michigan|Berrien Township]] to the north and northeast, [[Niles Township, Michigan|Niles Township]] to the east, [[Bertrand Township, Michigan|Bertrand Township]] to the south and southeast, [[Galien Township, Michigan|Galien Township]] to the southwest, [[Weesaw Township, Michigan|Weesaw Township]] to the west, and [[Baroda Township, Michigan|Baroda Township]] to the northwest.

No major highways transit the township, although [[U.S. Route 12 in Michigan|US 12]] parallels the southern edge and [[U.S. Route 31 in Michigan|US 31]] passes just to the east.

==Communities==
*'''Fort Sumter''' was a settlement on the south side of the St. Joseph River founded in the early 1860s.<ref>Walter Romig, ''Michigan Place Names'', p. 206</ref>

==Geography==
According to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the township has a total area of {{convert|33.2|sqmi|km2}}, of which, {{convert|32.3|sqmi|km2}} of it is land and {{convert|0.9|sqmi|km2}} of it (2.86%) is water.

The [[St. Joseph River (Lake Michigan)|St. Joseph River]] enters the township from the southeast, bends north by the city of Buchanan, and then flows mostly north through the eastern portion of the township.

==Demographics==
As of the [[census]]{{GR|2}} of 2000, there were 3,510 people, 1,317 households, and 1,023 families residing in the township.  The [[population density]] was 108.7 per square mile (42.0/km<U+00B2>).  There were 1,554 housing units at an average density of 48.1 per square mile (18.6/km<U+00B2>).  The racial makeup of the township was 96.18% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 1.20% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.48% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.26% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.43% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 1.45% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 1.25% of the population.

There were 1,317 households out of which 32.3% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 66.4% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 7.7% had a female householder with no husband present, and 22.3% were non-families. 18.2% of all households were made up of individuals and 7.4% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.66 and the average family size was 3.00.

In the township the population was spread out with 25.5% under the age of 18, 6.7% from 18 to 24, 27.8% from 25 to 44, 26.3% from 45 to 64, and 13.6% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 38 years. For every 100 females there were 106.3 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 101.9 males.

The median income for a household in the township was $40,503, and the median income for a family was $46,797. Males had a median income of $35,000 versus $24,274 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the township was $19,572.  About 4.6% of families and 5.2% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 5.8% of those under age 18 and 1.0% of those age 65 or over.

== Attractions ==

Bear Cave is a camping resort in the northern part of the township featuring a cave which was once a stop along the [[Underground Railroad]], assisting freed and escaped slaves from southern states to reach freedom in the northern states or Canada. The resort is on the St. Joseph River and offers canoeing and boating.

Nearby is [http://www.redbudmx.com/ Redbud Track 'N' Trail], an event site featuring professional as well as amateur [[Motocross|motocross racing]], known mostly for hosting a professional national on or near the [[Independence Day (United States)|4th of July]]. Attendance regularly reaches 30,000 for this weekend.

The {{convert|105|acre|km2|adj=on}} [[Fernwood Botanical Garden and Nature Preserve]] is located on the eastern bank of the St. Joseph River in the northeast corner of the township and is open year round.

[[Madron Lake]] is located within the township.

